interview-pipeline:
  description: "Full interview pipeline: generate data → build Bronze/Silver/Gold → explain"
  steps:
    - agent: databricks-code-gen
      prompt: "Phase 1 — Generate a synthetic dataset using Faker based on this interviewer prompt: $ORIGINAL\n\nCreate a Python notebook cell that generates realistic data with proper distributions, seeds, and saves as Delta tables. Include detailed narration comments."
    - agent: databricks-code-gen
      prompt: "Phase 2 — Build Silver layer SQL transforms for the tables created in Phase 1.\n\nOriginal prompt: $ORIGINAL\n\nPrevious step output:\n$INPUT\n\nCreate SQL cells for:\n1. CREATE TABLE with proper types (DECIMAL for money)\n2. CHECK constraints (ALTER TABLE ADD CONSTRAINT for amounts, valid enums)\n3. ROW_NUMBER dedup staging view → MERGE INTO (deterministic, idempotent)\n4. COALESCE nulls, UPPER/TRIM strings\n5. CLUSTER BY (business_key, date) + OPTIMIZE + ANALYZE TABLE\n6. Narration comments for every block\n\nEnd with a VALIDATION HARNESS: row counts, uniqueness check, rule violation counts, pruning-friendly sample query."
    - agent: databricks-code-gen
      prompt: "Phase 3 — Build Gold layer SQL for business analytics.\n\nOriginal prompt: $ORIGINAL\n\nPrevious steps:\n$INPUT\n\nCreate Gold tables with:\n1. CREATE TABLE + CHECK constraints + CLUSTER BY\n2. Idempotent window rebuild: DELETE WHERE date >= date_sub(current_date(), 14) then INSERT...SELECT for same window\n3. Aggregations (GROUP BY), window functions (running avg, rankings), CASE WHEN conditional aggregates, JOINs\n4. OPTIMIZE + ANALYZE TABLE\n5. Narration comments explaining Spark execution for each block\n\nEnd with a VALIDATION HARNESS: row counts across all 3 layers (Bronze >= Silver, Gold reconciles amounts), uniqueness on Gold grain, and a pruning-friendly sample query."
    - agent: spark-explainer
      prompt: "Phase 4 — Create a discussion guide for the pipeline built above.\n\nOriginal prompt: $ORIGINAL\n\nFull pipeline:\n$INPUT\n\nFor each major SQL block, explain:\n1. Transformation type (narrow/wide), shuffle points, join strategies\n2. How it scales to 1 billion rows (what becomes the bottleneck)\n3. The integrity enforcement story: how we enforce correctness without PK/FK (deterministic MERGE, CHECK constraints, validation harness, quarantine)\n4. Why Liquid Clustering was chosen over partitioning/Z-ORDER\n5. The 30-second 'think out loud' opening script\n\nFormat as talking points the user can say out loud to the interviewer."
